1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. b4 cxb4 4. d4 d5 {This is the main line of Smirnov
gambit.} 5. exd5 Qxd5 6. c4 bxc3 7. Nxc3 Qa5 8. d5 $5 {Along with a more solid
8.Bd2 move, White has this 8.d5 idea, continuing his gambit style play.} Qxc3+
9. Bd2 Qf6 {Black can move his queen elsewhere, but it doesn't change the
overall situation. White is ahead in development and is going to play actively.
} 10. dxc6 bxc6 (10... Qxc6 {would give White an extra tempo after} 11. Rc1 Qd6
{White's position is so powerful that he can rush into the attack:} 12. Rxc8+
Rxc8 13. Qa4+ Kd8 (13... Qc6 $2 {fails due to} 14. Bb5) 14. Qxa7 {White is
playing in the gambit style of 'old masters'. Now he's threatening Ba5 with a
powerful attack of Black's centralized king.}) 11. Rc1 e6 $2 {This move is
wrong, but it's not so easy for Black to find a safe way to continue his
development.} (11... e5 12. Qa4 {attacking c6-pawn} Bd7 13. Bc4 {threatening
Ng5, along with many other threats}) 12. Bb5 $1 {The only reason for this
shocking sacrifice is to secure White's king! Sounds strange, but you'll get
it soon.} ({Instant} 12. Bg5 {does not work because of} Bb4+ (12... Qf5 $2 13.
Qd8#) 13. Ke2 Qb2+ {White's exposed king causes troubles to White.}) 12... cxb5
13. Bg5 Bb4+ 14. Kf1 {Since White gave away his f1-bishop, now he can use this
square for his king. Now Black loses his queen in view of Qd8 checkmate threat.
} 1-0

