1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. b4 Nxb4 4. c3 Nc6 5. d4 d5 {Black refrains from the
eventual exchange on d4. In this line, White can't develop his knight to c3,
but it has another perspective root.} 6. exd5 Qxd5 7. Na3 $1 {The knight is
ready to continue his way to b5 (threatening Nc7 fork), and in the meanwhile
it's supporting Bc4 move.} Bg4 {The most aggressively looking response.} 8. Bc4
{developing his piece with a tempo} Bxf3 9. gxf3 Qh5 {Black broke White's pawn
structure, but had to pay his price for it: for lack of light-squared bishop,
Black's light squares became vulnerabe.} 10. Qb3 {Taking aim at b7 and f7
pawns.} (10. Rb1 {is interesting as well}) 10... O-O-O 11. Bxf7 {It's not that
White wants the f7-pawn that much, rather he wants to get control over
e6-square.} Qxf3 12. Be6+ {From here the bishop is blockading Black's position,
and taking control over g4-squre.} Kb8 13. O-O {White can castle safely: even
though his castling is exposed, Black has only his queen available for the
attack, but it doesn't have any good squares to go.} Nf6 $2 {Surprizingly,
this standard move is losing quickly.} 14. Rb1 b6 (14... Na5 15. Qb5 {doesn't
help Black - he's still defenseless}) 15. dxc5 {and White is winning} *

