1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. b4 cxb4 4. d4 e6 {Black uses a tricky way to
counter-attack} 5. d5 (5. a3 {is a more solid way for White} d5 6. e5 bxa3 7.
c3 {for the sacrificed pawn, White obtained good attacking chances. He can
trade off the dark-squared bishops by playing Ba3, while the b1-knight can be
transferred to a3-b5-d6.}) 5... Qf6 {attacking White's rook} 6. c3 {the only
normal way to close f6-a1 diagonal for Black's queen.} bxc3 7. dxc6 c2 {Black
managed to capture White's rook, but it's not the end...} 8. Qxc2 Qxa1 9. e5 $1
{Suddenly, the a1-queen has no way to escape.} Bb4+ {This natual move turns
out to be a mistake. It closes b-file, and gives White an extra tempo for a3
move in some variations.} (9... bxc6 $1 {Black is ready to play Rb8, and White
needs to close the line.} 10. Bc4 Rb8 11. Bb3 {now White is ready to capture
the queen by playing Bb2, Black has to hurry up with his counter-threats.} Bb4+
12. Kd1 Ba6 13. Bb2 Bd3 {it's quite unlikely that your opponent can find such
moves during a practical game} 14. Bxa1 Bxc2+ 15. Kxc2 {dust settled, and we
reached an approximately equal endgame.}) 10. Kd1 {White can't move his minor
pieces as it would free Black's a1-prisoner!} bxc6 (10... Ne7 11. a3 Ba5 12.
Bb2 {and the queen is trapped} Qa2 13. Bc4 $18) 11. Bc4 $1 {preparing Bb2} (11.
a3 {leads to unnecessary complications:} Rb8 12. axb4 Rxb4) 11... d5 12. Bb3 {
Black has no normal defense against Bb2 move.} *

