Bd2 (8. d5 e6 9. Bd2 Bb4 {could transpose into the same position}) 8... e6 9.
d5 {White sacrifices a pawn to open up more lines for his attack. It's a risky
choice for White, but Black is not safe either :)} Bb4 {counterblow. Black
doesn't want to slow down his development,} 10. Qc1 {not only protecting
c3-knight but also preparing a3-move.} exd5 11. a3 {attacking the bishop, and
indirectly - Black's queen!} Bd6 (11... Bxc3 12. Bxc3 {[%cal Gc3a5,Gc3g7]}) 12.
Bb5 {White should strive for a quick development and active play.} Nge7 13. Ne4
$1 {[%cal Gd2a5] discovered attack} Qd8 (13... Qxb5 {fails to} 14. Nxd6+ {fork}
) 14. Nxd6+ Qxd6 15. Bb4 {taking advantage of a pin on Black's c6-knight} Qe6+
16. Kd1 {Played to enable Re1 on the next move.} Qf6 17. Re1 {Despite of
White's somewhat unusual play, he has finished development of his pieces. Most
of the Black's pieces are either undeveloped or pinned.} Kd8 ({perhaps Black
should have given up the exchange} 17... O-O 18. Bxc6 Nxc6 19. Bxf8 Kxf8 20.
Qc5+ {with an unclear position}) 18. Bc3 {White keeps attacking by his every
move.} Qd6 (18... Qg6 19. Qf4 {with multiple threats: Ng5/Ne5, Rc1 etc}) 19.
Bxc6 {eliminating the defenders of Black's king} Qxc6 (19... Nxc6 20. Qg5+ {
with a strong attack}) 20. Rxe7 $1 {now Black's king is left alone...} Kxe7 21.
Qg5+ Ke8 (21... Kd6 22. Bb4+ Kc7 23. Rc1 {winning the queen and the game}) (
21... Kd7 22. Ne5+ {fork}) 22. Qxg7 Rf8 23. Bb4 {Black is defenseless.} *

