position} 4. d4 d5 5. exd5 Qxd5 6. c4 bxc3 7. Nxc3) 4. c3 {White is gaining
tempos to build a strong pawn center.} Nc6 5. d4 cxd4 6. cxd4 d5 7. exd5 Qxd5
8. Nc3 Qa5 9. Bd2 {Protecting the knight and preparing an eventual discovered
attack on Black's queen.} e6 10. Bd3 {This bishop is going to attack Black's
castling in the middlegame.} Bb4 {developing a piece with a tempo} 11. Qc2 {
White needs to protect the knight. Additionally White's Q+B battery will
pressure h7 pawn.} Nf6 ({Here Black can use a sudden opportunity to equalize
the game:} 11... Bxc3 12. Bxc3 Nb4 13. Qb1 Nxd3+ 14. Qxd3 Qa6 {Now White has
to trade off the queens, otherwise he will not be able to castle.} 15. Qxa6
bxa6 {Although Black is a pawn up, this doubled pawn doesn't have much value.
The opposite-colored bishops guarantee a draw. If White dislikes his isolated
pawn-d4, he can trade it off right away:} 16. d5) 12. O-O O-O 13. a3 {White
has finished his opening development, and now should start attacking.} Bxc3 (
13... Be7 {is not losing but looks scary for Black} 14. Ne4 {Attacking the
queen, and (after the exchange of knights) h7-pawn.} Qh5 15. Rfb1 {planning to
keep chasing Black's queen by playing Rb5}) 14. Bxc3 Qd5 15. Rab1 {Taking aim
at b7-pawn and preparing Rb5.} b6 {Black needs to develop his bishop somehow.}
16. Rb5 Qd6 17. d5 {opening the lines for all of White's pieces.} Nxd5 $2 {
This natural move loses the game} (17... exd5 18. Bxf6 Qxf6 19. Bxh7+ {looks
dangerous for Black, but in reality White can't continue his attack
effectively.}) 18. Bxh7+ Kh8 19. Be4 {putting pressure on Black's central
pieces, and brining White's light-squared bishop 'back to home'.} Ba6 20. Ng5
$1 {White ignores Black's threats. Who cares about the rook, when you can
simply checkmate your opponent?} Bxb5 21. Bxd5 {[%cal Gc2h7] Threatening Qh7#}
f5 22. Qd1 {the queen finds another root to h-file.} exd5 23. Qh5+ Qh6 (23...
Kg8 24. Qh7#) 24. Qxh6+ {the pawn is pinned and can't move.} Kg8 25. Qxg7# *

